  "description": [
    "Reviewing Anne Parrish Offers A Social Document And a Vork of Art POOR CHILD By Anne Parrish Harpers 250 By MaryCarter Roberts The casual phrase which Anne Parrish uses as title for this novel is in perfect harmony with the story which the novel tells For it is a tale of cruelty which is masterly in its casualness One often says poor child without meaning pity One says it without any feeling or thought Similarly Miss Parrish gives us a child born to poverty and shows how benevolence without feeling or thought is casually be stowed upon him and traces the disastrous results It is hard to describe the suave elegance of her presentation of her sordid material The child is one Martin Doyle a 12yearold boy who has lived his whole life in city slums After his mother in a fit of insanity has murdered his sister and committed suicide he is sent by a selfappoint ed protect to the summer home of a family of great wealth No length for his iMt is prescribed He sim ply arrives in an atmosphere which to him is paradisical and is told to feel at home The most charming graciousness is"
  ],
